    <h2 id="why-citrulline">Why Citrulline Is the Most Underrated Performance Supplement in Your Gym Bag</h2>

    <p>Citrulline is an amino acid named after <em>Citrullus lanatus</em> — the watermelon from which it was first isolated in 1930. Despite nearly a century of research, citrulline remained in the shadow of arginine (marketed as the "nitric oxide booster") until the scientific community recognized a paradox: oral arginine is a poor way to increase nitric oxide because 40-60% is destroyed by intestinal and hepatic arginase before it ever reaches your bloodstream. Citrulline bypasses this first-pass metabolism entirely. It is absorbed intact, converted to arginine in the kidneys, and then converted to nitric oxide — delivering 2-3 times the nitric oxide boost of equivalent arginine doses.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">53%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">greater increase in plasma arginine levels from oral citrulline supplementation compared to oral arginine supplementation itself, according to a 2017 study in the <em>British Journal of Clinical Pharmacology</em>. Citrulline is, paradoxically, the best way to raise arginine — and therefore nitric oxide — in your body.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Nitric oxide (NO) is the molecule behind "the pump." When NO is released by endothelial cells lining your blood vessels, it signals the smooth muscle to relax, widening the vessel (vasodilation) and increasing blood flow. During exercise, this means more oxygen and glucose delivered to working muscles, more efficient removal of lactate and ammonia, and that visible, satisfying vascularity that signals productive training. A 2019 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Strength and Conditioning Research</em> confirmed that citrulline supplementation significantly improved both high-intensity exercise performance and aerobic endurance across 12 controlled studies.</p>

