      <cite>JSCR, 2010 — trained males, bench press protocol</cite>
    </div>

    <h3>L-Citrulline vs. Citrulline Malate: Which Form Is Better?</h3>

    <p>L-citrulline is the pure amino acid. Citrulline malate (CM) bonds L-citrulline with malic acid, typically at a 2:1 ratio (2g citrulline per 1g malate). The malic acid component participates in the Krebs cycle, potentially enhancing aerobic ATP production. Most exercise performance studies used citrulline malate at 6-8g doses. However, gram-for-gram of actual citrulline content, pure L-citrulline raises plasma arginine levels more effectively because there is no malate diluting the dose. For gummy supplements — where total payload per gummy is limited — pure L-citrulline generally provides more citrulline per serving.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128161;</span>
      <p><strong>Dosing tip:</strong> The clinical dose is 3-6g L-citrulline or 6-8g citrulline malate. Most gummies deliver 1-3g per serving. Take them 30-60 minutes before training. For maximum pump, combine gummies with powder to reach the full clinical dose. On rest days, 2-3g maintains baseline NO levels for improved cardiovascular health.</p>
    </div>

