    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Citrulline Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What does citrulline do for exercise performance?</summary><p>Citrulline increases nitric oxide production, dilating blood vessels and improving blood flow to muscles. This enhances oxygen delivery, waste removal, pump, endurance, and recovery between sets.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between L-citrulline and citrulline malate?</summary><p>L-citrulline is the pure amino acid. Citrulline malate adds malic acid (typically 2:1). For equal citrulline content, pure L-citrulline raises arginine more effectively. Citrulline malate may offer additional ATP production from malic acid.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much citrulline should I take for a pump?</summary><p>The clinical dose is 3-6g L-citrulline or 6-8g citrulline malate, 30-60 minutes before training. Most gummies provide 1-3g — you may need multiple servings or a powder supplement for the full clinical dose.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>When should I take citrulline gummies?</summary><p>30-60 minutes before training for pump and performance. Citrulline peaks in plasma within 60-90 minutes. On rest days, take at any time to maintain baseline NO levels.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is citrulline better than arginine for nitric oxide?</summary><p>Yes. Oral citrulline raises plasma arginine 53% more than oral arginine because citrulline bypasses first-pass metabolism that destroys 40-60% of ingested arginine.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are citrulline gummies as effective as powder?</summary><p>Gummies typically deliver lower doses (1-3g) vs. powder (3-6g). For recreational athletes, gummies provide meaningful NO support. Serious athletes should consider combining gummies with powder.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does citrulline have side effects?</summary><p>Citrulline is well-tolerated. Mild GI effects may occur above 10g. Use caution with blood pressure medications or PDE5 inhibitors due to additive vasodilation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I stack citrulline with other supplements?</summary><p>Citrulline stacks well with caffeine, beta-alanine, creatine, and beetroot extract. Avoid stacking with high-dose arginine as they compete for the same pathway.</p></details>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> Citrulline may lower blood pressure through vasodilation. If you take antihypertensive medications or PDE5 inhibitors, consult your physician before supplementing. Citrulline is not a substitute for medical treatment of hypertension or erectile dysfunction.</p>
    </div>

